The adsorption/desorption isotherms of the samples (Fig. 2
                        ) confirm a mesoporous structure, corresponding to the IUPAC type 4 classification. The surface areas of Ni(0) and Ni@CQDs (ethanol) samples are 19.52 m2 g⁻1 and 13,806 m2 g⁻1, respectively. Both the BET surface area and pore diameter are reduced in the Ni@CQDs (ethanol) catalyst compared to Ni(0) (Table 1
                        ). This reduction may be due to the CQDs occupying part of the available surface area when dispersed on the nickel catalyst. As a result, some pores may shrink or become blocked, leading to a decrease in both pore volume and surface area. However, the CQDs enhance electron transfer and active site stability, which can counterbalance these effects, resulting in improved catalytic activity in hydrolysis reactions [57].

By analyzing the change in concentration over time relative to temperature data, it was found that the hydrolysis reactions followed a zero-order kinetic equation. The data obtained for the hydrolysis of KBH4 using the Ni@CQDs catalyst at various temperatures were evaluated using the Arrhenius equation to calculate the activation energy of the hydrolysis reactions (Fig. 13
                        ). Additionally, the Eyring-Polanyi equation was employed to calculate the values of ΔH# and ΔS#. The calculated values are presented in Table 3
                        .
